Class Solution

java.lang.Object
  Solution

public class Solution
extends java.lang.Object

This class models a TSP solution.

Internal structure of the class:
This solution itself is stored in the array m_solution.
m_solution[i] should be the index of the element at index i in the solution.
The attribute m_nbVertices is the number of vertices in the problem.
The array m_solution has size m_nbVertices+1 and it should start with the first vertex for the route and end with the same vertex.
For example, suppose a problem with 5 customers (hence, the corresponding vertices index range from 0 to 4), the following array represents a TSP solution (tour) that visit all customers by index order:
m_solution = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 0];

A recommendation is to always have m_solution[0]=m_solution[m_nbVertices]= 0.

So a complete feasible solution should respect the following rules:

  • m_solution[0]=m_solution[m_nbVertices]
  • Apart from the vertex at indices 0 and m_nbVertices, each customer index should be represented once and only one in m_solution.

    Creating, accessing or modifying a solution:
    A Solution object is created for a given TSP problem, represented by an Instance object.
    Let ist be an object of class Instance, the following code creates a solution for this problem:

    Solution mysol = new Solution(ist);

    During its creation, this object is initialized with vertex 0 at all position. It should be modified to represent a feasible solution.
    This modification is done by the method setVertexPosition(int s, int i), which sets vertex s at position i in the solution. For example, the following code creates a TSP solution that visits all customers in increasing vertex order:

    for (int i=0; i < ist.getNbVertices(); i++) { mysol.setVertexPosition(i, i); } mysol.setVertexPosition(0, ist.getNbVertices());

    To explore a Solution object, the vertex at position i can be obtained calling getSolution(int).
    The validate() method allows to check the feasibility of a solution.
    To calculate the cost of a solution, you can call evaluate().

    Note that evaluate() recomputes every distance from zero. If you do a slight modification of the solution it is less time consuming to update yourself the cost of the modified solution using the function setObjective(long newval ).

    reverse

    public void reverse(int firstIdx,
                    int lastIdx)
             throws java.lang.Exception
    reverse the sequence of vertices in the solution that range between indices firstIdx and lastIdx (both included).
    The objective function is updated according to the modification.

    For example, if the solution is [0,1,2,3,4,0], reverse(2,4) produces solution [0,1,4,3,2,0].

    Throws:
    java.lang.Exception - produces an error if the indices are not valid.

    validate

    public boolean validate()
                 throws java.lang.Exception
    Check that the solution is feasible.
    The performed tests are the following :
  • m_solution[0]=m_solution[m_nbVertices]
  • Apart from the vertex at indices 0 and m_nbVertices, each customer index should be represented once and only one in m_solution.
    The cost is recomputed.
    When an error is met, the error code can be obtained calling the method getError().

    Returns:
    true if the solution is feasible false otherwise.
    Throws:
    java.lang.Exception

    • print

    public void print(java.io.PrintStream out)
    Print the solution on output out. The solution is printed using vertices numbers and not labels. For example if you want to print a solution mysol on the screen, use : mysol.print(System.err); Reminder: do not print on System.out.

    Parameters:
    out - : output
